menu "Hyperwisor IoT"

# --------------- Core (always on) ---------------

config HYPERWISOR_CMD_MAX_HANDLERS
    int "Maximum number of command handlers"
    default 16
    range 1 64
    help
      Upper bound on the number of cloud command handlers that can be
      registered via hyperwisor_register_cmd_handler(). Each handler
      consumes a small fixed slot. 16 is enough for most projects.

config HYPERWISOR_HTTP_BASE_URL
    string "HTTP API base URL"
    default "https://hyperwisor.nikolaindustry.workers.dev/functions/v1"
    help
      Base URL for the Hyperwisor HTTP API (database, SMS, auth,
      onboarding). All API paths are appended to this URL.
      Change this if you are self-hosting the backend.

config HYPERWISOR_WS_HOST
    string "WebSocket server hostname"
    default "nikolaindustry-realtime.onrender.com"
    help
      Hostname of the Hyperwisor realtime server. The library connects
      to wss://<host>:<port>/?id=<deviceId>.

config HYPERWISOR_WS_PORT
    int "WebSocket server port"
    default 443
    range 1 65535

# --------------- Feature gates ---------------

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_SYSTEM
    bool "System commands (restart, status)"
    default y
    help
      Register the built-in SYSTEM command handler (restart, uptime,
      device info). This is nearly free in code size and is recommended
      for all deployments.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_NTP
    bool "NTP time sync"
    default y
    help
      Sync the device clock via SNTP after WiFi connects. Required
      for accurate timestamps in logs and cloud events.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_HTTP
    bool "HTTP helper"
    default y
    help
      Expose hyperwisor_http_get/post helpers. Used by the widget
      module and useful for application-level HTTP calls.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_WIDGET
    bool "Dashboard widget updates"
    default y
    help
      Enable the widget API (update_widget_string, show_dialog, etc.)
      so the device can push live data to the Hyperwisor dashboard.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_OTA
    bool "Over-the-air firmware updates"
    default n
    select ESP_HTTPS_OTA
    select BOOTLOADER_APP_ROLLBACK
    help
      When enabled, the library registers an OTA_UPDATE command
      handler. The Hyperwisor dashboard can push firmware updates
      automatically — zero user code required.

      You MUST also switch to an OTA partition table. Copy the
      correct partitions_XXmb_ota.csv from the hyperwisor component's
      partitions/ directory and add to sdkconfig.defaults:

        CONFIG_PARTITION_TABLE_CUSTOM=y
        CONFIG_PARTITION_TABLE_CUSTOM_FILENAME="partitions_16mb_ota.csv"

      The build system will validate this at compile time and print a
      clear error if the partition table is missing OTA slots.

      WARNING: Without Secure Boot V2, OTA firmware is NOT verified.
      Anyone who can send an OTA command can push arbitrary firmware.
      Enable Secure Boot V2 for production deployments.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_GPIO
    bool "GPIO management from cloud"
    default n
    help
      Allow the Hyperwisor dashboard to read/write GPIO pins.
      Only pins listed in the board port's managed_gpios array are
      accessible — all others are silently rejected for safety.

      If no board port is provided (headless deployment), GPIO
      management is effectively disabled even if this option is on.

config HYPERWISOR_ENABLE_DISPLAY
    bool "Display brightness control"
    default n
    help
      Enable display backlight control via the board port callbacks
      (backlight_set, backlight_set_level, backlight_get_level).
      The library itself is UI-framework-agnostic — it only calls
      the port function pointers. The app layer provides the actual
      implementation (e.g. LVGL overlay, LEDC PWM, or I2C command).

      If no board port is provided or the callbacks are NULL, this
      feature is inert.

endmenu
